EVCS - Consumption Prediction of Netherland¶

In this analysis, we will build a Machine Learning model using Random Forest algorithm based on a EVCS dataset in Netherland to explore the relationships between energy consumption and all other features.¶

Fit Weibull Distribution¶

In [19]:
# Weibull Distribution
from scipy.stats import weibull_min 
plt.hist(df["ChargeTime"], bins=100, density=True, alpha=0.5) 
shape, loc, scale = weibull_min.fit(df["ChargeTime"], floc=0) 
x = np.linspace(df["ChargeTime"].min(), df["ChargeTime"].max(), 100) 
plt.plot(x, weibull_min(shape, loc, scale).pdf(x)) 
plt.title("Weibull fit on ChargeTime data") 
plt.xlabel("ChargeTime")
Out[19]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'ChargeTime')
In [20]:
# CDF for Weibull Distribution
import statsmodels.distributions 
ecdf=statsmodels.distributions.ECDF(df["ChargeTime"]) 
plt.plot(x,ecdf(x),label="ChargeTimeCDF") 
plt.plot(x,weibull_min(shape,loc,scale).cdf(x), label="Weibullfit")
plt.title("Charge time CDF") 
plt.xlabel("ChargeTime") 
plt.legend()
Out[20]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f98898e4110>
In [21]:
# Probility plot of Weibull
from scipy.stats import probplot, weibull_min 
probplot(df["ChargeTime"], dist=weibull_min(shape,loc,scale), plot=plt.figure().add_subplot(111)) 
plt.title("Weibull probability plot of ChargeTime")
Out[21]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Weibull probability plot of ChargeTime')
In [23]:
# Percent-Point Function
import scipy.stats
scipy.stats.weibull_min(shape, loc, scale).ppf(0.8)
Out[23]:
4.564751407814518
Our dataset is well fitted in Weibull Distribution, and above percent-point function would give the discrete outcome that is less than or equal to a probability. i.e. In above cell, the result illustrates 80% of charging time is no longer than 4.56 hours.¶

In [66]:
def chartsns(occurance_list):
    hour_list = [t.hour for t in occurance_list]
    numbers=[x for x in range(0,24)]
    labels=map(lambda x: str(x), numbers)
    plt.xticks(numbers, labels)
    plt.xlim(0,24)
    sns.distplot(hour_list)
    plt.show()

# Ref: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8369584/plot-histogram-of-datetime-time-python-matplotlib
In [67]:
chartsns(df["TransactionStartTime"])
We can identify that most of the charging behavior started at 4am, peaked at 7am and kept steady until about 5pm, then started to decline. It is obviously that most charging events occured between 7am and 5pm.¶

# Label encoding 
dn = {'Day':1, 'Night':0}
X_['Day/Night'] = X_['Day/Night'].map(dn)

peak = {'ON PEAK':2, 'MID PEAK':1, 'OFF PEAK':0}
X_['Peak'] = X_['Peak'].map(peak)

season = {'Spring':1, 'Summer':2, 'Autumn':3, 'Winter':4}
X_['Season'] = X_['Season'].map(season)

dow = {'Monday':1, 'Tuesday':2, 'Wednesday':3, 'Thursday':4, 'Friday':5, 'Saturday':6, 'Sunday':7}
X_['Day of the Week'] = X_['Day of the Week'].map(dow)

# Hpyer-parameters
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 100, stop = 1000, num = 10)]
max_features = ["auto", "sqrt"]
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(5, 30, num = 6)]

mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_true["TotalEnergy"] - predictions["Predictions"]) / np.abs(y_true["TotalEnergy"])))
print('Accuracy:', round(100*(1 - mape), 2), "%")

Accuracy: 87.33 %
We built a prediction model based on Random Forest algorithm to make predictions on Total Energy. Hyper-parameters are tuned by using Randomized Search function, and cross-validation applied for generalisation purpose. The model returns a Mean-square Error (MSE) of 12.43, a Root-mean-square Error (RMSE) of 3.53, and an accuracy of 87.33%.¶
Our prediction model result reveals that there's quite a strong relationship between the charge time period and the total energy consumption. In future work, we would like to investigate in-depth how the charge time / total energy would vary depending on different locations and regions.¶
